    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Abinger Hall | Dorking</placeName>
                    <date>March 10<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> 1880<ref target="#foot.f1"/></date>
                    <salute>My dear M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Fox</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I write only a word to thank you for your second most kind letter. I am glad that your poor dear Father’s sufferings are over, &amp; that his end was so tranquil.<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
                    <p>I have now before my eyes his bright face as a young man, so full of intelligence &amp; I hear his voice as clearly as if he were present. Your mother<ref target="#foot.f3"/> must have gone through terrible suffering during his long illness.</p>
                    <p>My wife joins me in saying how deeply we sympathise with her. Pray believe me | Yours very sincerely | Charles Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="tnotes">
                <note xml:id="tnote.n1">0.1 Abinger Hall | Dorking] <hi rend="italic">above del</hi> ‘<hi rend="italic">Down, | Beckenham, Kent. | Railway Station | Orpington. S.E.R.</hi>’ </note>
            </div>
            
            
        </div>
        
        
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The month is established by the postmark. CD wrote March in error.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-12569.xml">letter from C. W. Fox, 8 April 1880</ref>; <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1730.xml">William Darwin Fox</ref> had died on 8 April 1880.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1711.xml">Ellen Sophia Fox</ref>.</note>
        </div>
    
